# Project Structure Conventions

## Directory Layout

When starting a new project, create this structure inside a project-specific directory:

```
<project-name>/
├── docs/
│   ├── requirements/
│   │   ├── 00-project-brief.md
│   │   ├── 01-requirements.md
│   │   └── glossary.md
│   ├── architecture/
│   │   ├── 00-system-overview.md
│   │   ├── api-spec.md
│   │   ├── data-model.md
│   │   └── adr/
│   │       └── ADR-001-<slug>.md
│   ├── design/
│   │   ├── 00-user-flows.md
│   │   ├── 01-design-system.md
│   │   ├── screens/
│   │   │   └── <screen-name>.md
│   │   └── components/
│   │       └── <component-name>.md
│   └── reviews/
│       └── review-<date>-<scope>.md
├── src/
├── tests/
├── README.md
└── ...
```

## Document Conventions

- All documentation in Markdown
- Diagrams in Mermaid syntax (renderable in GitHub/Cursor)
- Use relative links between documents
- Date format: YYYY-MM-DD
- File naming: kebab-case, numbered prefixes for ordered documents

## Cross-Referencing

Documents should reference each other to maintain traceability:

- Requirements → referenced by Architecture docs (e.g., "Implements REQ-003")
- Architecture → referenced by Design docs (e.g., "Based on ADR-002")
- Design → referenced by Engineers in code comments and commit messages
- Reviews → reference specific requirements and code locations
